snippet.textDisplay:
Update: Walmart & Aldi near St. Louis Missouri Metro East. Shopping experience on 3/23/2020 10:00 am.
Aldi quiet out of generic ritz crackers and toilet paper. Paper towls in stock 2 per person. Only me and my mom had face protection on. None of the workers or other shoppers. Roughly about 20 shoppers. ************Praise They taped hand sanitizer to their card readers!!!! A+++++ Very innovative. While me and my mom were slightly trolled by a big macho guy. We had little conversation about well that's not going to stop nothing. We both agree'd if I had it would prevent me from spreading it. As we were bagging on the counter he took his stuff to his car to bag..... Very good there awareness is happening. That is a very good passive tip he gave us. Bag outside minimize time inside food places.

Walmart. As we approached a nice lady was sanitizing the carts in the breeze way *******Praise A+++++++ Excellent Idea. No workers had masks. The food delivery cart people gathering delievery items had no masks. We did notice more shoppers at Walmart wearing masks. Not sure if they had toilet paper did not look. Over all stock looks to be about 30% less. Limits on cereal and dry goods prolly good idea (rice pasta). We did notice social distancing even in parking lot. Very nice. During parking lot experience. Though maybe the outdoor garden center would be good place for seniors to shop for their items. A special place for them so they don't have to go inside.

My mother came up with a mask hack. Cause medical works don't have them how we normal people going to. She took a new pair of loose sweatpants with the loose elastic at the bottom and cut about 6 inches up from the bottom. with the elastic part face up pull over head and and then lift up over mouth and nose. They stood up just fine. Cut two side slits to slip over ears to keep it up without having to mess around with it. THINK TURTLE NECK PULLED OVER FACE WITH LITTLE SLITS ON BOTH SIDES TO SLIP OVER EARS TO KEEP IT UP. MAYBE A SWIFTER LINER INSIDE THAT. Don't get scented swifter! don't cut swifter they string bad. just pad it. Wearing it will need to relax to breath otherwise breathing will be little more difficult than without the mask. Have to try the swifter hack around the house get used to breathing with it on. ONE OF THE GREATEST MOMS IN THE WORLD. We poor people are street smart.

Poor people payment suggestion: Mailing millions of checks for people go cash and get paper money not the best idea in health crisis. We need the $$$ sent to something like Illionis Link / Snap system.

snippet.textDisplay:
To prevent infection and to slow transmission of COVID-19, do the following:
1- Wash your hands regularly with soap and water, or clean them with alcohol-based hand rub.
2- Maintain at least 1 metre distance between you and people coughing or sneezing.
3- Avoid touching your face.
4- Cover your mouth and nose when coughing or sneezing.
5- Stay home if you feel unwell.
6- Refrain from smoking and other activities that weaken the lungs.
7- Practice physical distancing by avoiding unnecessary travel and staying away from large groups of people.

snippet.textDisplay: I’m a medical professional in Thailand and seeing what happened in Italy absolutely terrifies me. We have a notoriously horrific government, they have done nothing but make disastrous decisions and jeopardize and threaten the healthcare workforce. Our number is starting to go up because of it and a few millions people fled the capital city just a few days ago. I’m so afraid that in 2 weeks time, this will spread to every region of the country and the number of cases will grow beyond our capacity. Even in normal circumstance, Thai healthcare is already overloaded and overworked. We have always had beds in the corridors and 50 inpatients/ 1 doctor is the norm. I can’t imagine how we would handle the influx of cases in an uncontrollable pandemic.

snippet.textDisplay:
AND such things happened nontheless despite the time those governments have when China got hit hard and implemented almost a curfew. They simply saw it happen, did almost nothing, and wouldn't act until the infection almost went out of control, as they should have weeks ago. Similar things happened in Italy, UK, and likely US now. It's kinda ironic how some medias were accusing China for "damaging personal liberties" during its quanrantine, even New York Times itself (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BTE6cLI8y9c). And see where we are right now.
As an international college student in Michigan, I saw how it affected my parents back home first, watched how it developed and escalated while the current Administration kept telling people it would be "fine" while senators sold stocks right before self-isolation was implemented and stock market dived. It was an unfortunate development, but shockingly similar to what happened in Wuhan back in December: they were trying to cover it up, in some degree (https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/02/27/us-workers-without-protective-gear-assisted-coronavirus-evacuees-hhs-whistleblower-says/).
Sad. People should be aware of what's happening among their presumably "free" medias and "democratic" governments. I felt disillusioned.
